It is well known that Li is an alkali earth metal and located in the 3rd chemical element of the periodic table, belonging to group IA and Period 2. It is the lightest metal element with the smallest atomic weight (6.941 g mol−1) and a low density of 0.534 g cm−3, which is less than that of oil, so that it must be stored in oil to avoid reacting with ambient air. In addition, Li is a silvery white color soft metal along with a small ionic radius of 76 pm for Li+ (Fig. 3
                     a). Considering the electronic configuration: 1s22s1, Li atom is prone to release the outermost electron for reaching stable state, which means that it owns a high reactivity and is extremely sensitive to ambient air, including oxygen (O2), carbon dioxide (CO2), and nitrogen(N2). Of particular note, moisture is inevitable in ambient air and its content can increase with humidity increase. Once exposed to ambient air, Li metal can inevitably react with these components (detailed chemical reaction formulas are presented in Table 1
                     ) [78,79]. It can be seen that the reaction products are composed of inorganic compounds, like Li2O, Li2CO3, Li3N, and LiOH, which have been widely accepted as the main components of naturally formed SEI film on the surface of commercial Li metal. Recently, it was pointed out by Han et al. [80] that Li2CO3 was found to be unstable in the SEI film on the surface of Li metal by combining aberration-corrected cryo-electron microscopy (cryo-EM) and theoretical calculation (25Li + 6Li2CO3 = LiC6 + 18Li2O; ΔG = -2653 kJ mol−1).
